Components-

COmponents mail building blocks of an Angular application.

A component is a TypeScript class that is decorated with the @Component decorator.

The @Component decorator provides metadata about the component, such as its selector, template, and styles

The selector is a CSS selector that identifies the component in the HTML template.
 
- Typescript class that contains behaviors such as handling user input and fetching data from a server.

-Component must have the HTML template that controls what renders into the DOM 

-Also, CSS selector that defines how the component is used in the HTML template.
 
 
Component Lifecycle-

A component's lifecycle refers to the sequence of events that happens between component creation and destruction.

Each step represents a different part of Angular's process for rendering components and managing their state.
 
1. Constructor- The constructor is called when the component is created. 

It is used to initialize the component's properties and inject dependencies.
 
2. ngOnInit- runs once after angular has initialized all the component's input
 
 
Component Communication-

@Input and @Output decorators are used to facilitate communication between components in Angular.

@Input is used to pass data from a parent component to a child component, 

Parent Component----Data Flow---->Child Component
 
 
while @Output is used to emit events from a child component to a parent component.

Child Component----Event Flow---->Parent Component

Child componnet uses the @Output decorator to raise an event to notify the parent component of the change.

To raise an event , an @Output decorator must have the type of EventEmitter, 

which is a class provided by @angular/core that allows you to create and emit custom events.
 
Data Binding / Interpolation- it refers to embedding the expressions into markup text.

- By default Interpolation uses double curly braces {{}} to bind data from the component to the template.

- It is used to display dynamic data in the template, such as the value of a variable

- Using Data binding we can bind the data from the component to the template and also bind the events from the template to the component.
 
Angular support one way and two way data binding.

One way data binding is used to bind data from the component to the template.

One way Data binding can be achieved using interpolation, property binding and event binding.

Interpolation is used to bind data from the component to the template, using double curly braces {{}}.

Property binding is used to bind data from the component to the template, using square brackets [].

    - proprety binding helps to set the values for properties of html elements, directives and components.

    - Use Property Binding to do things like toggle the disabled state of a button, 

    set the source of an image, or apply CSS classes conditionally.

    - here this binding moves the value in one direction, from the component's property into

    target element's property.

Event binding is used to bind events from the template to the component, using parentheses ().
 
 
Two way data binding is used to bind data from the component to the template 

and also bind the events from the template to the component.

It can be implemented with or without using the ngModel directive.

Without ngModel directive - this is possible by using property binding and event binding together.

$event is a special variable that contains the event object that is passed to the event handler when an event is triggered.
 
 
Angular Directives-

- Directives are built in classes in Angular  using which we can add behavior and 

we can maniulate the DOM elements in the template.

- three types of directives in Angular are:

1. Component Directives- these are the directives that are used to create components in Angular.

2. Structural Directives- these are the directives that are used to change the structure of the

DOM by adding or removing elements from the DOM.

Built in- structural directives are *ngIf, *ngFor, *ngSwitch.

3. Attribute Directives- these are the directives that are used to change the appearance or

behavior of an element, component or another directive.

ngClass - add or remove CSS classes based on conditions.

ngStyle - add or remove inline styles based on conditions.

ngModel - used for two way data binding in forms.
 
Angular Pipes-

- Pipes are nothing but angular functions to use in template expressions to accept a value 

and return a transformed value.

- Use pipes to transform strings, currency amounts, dates, and other data for display.

- Build In Angular Pipes are:

1. DatePipe- used to format date values in the template.

2. CurrencyPipe- used to format currency values in the template.

3. DecimalPipe- used to format decimal values in the template.

4. PercentPipe- used to format percentage values in the template.

5. JsonPipe- used to convert a JavaScript object into a JSON string for display in the template.

6. SlicePipe- used to create a new array or string containing a subset of the elements.

7. UpperCasePipe- used to transform a string to uppercase in the template.

8. LowerCasePipe- used to transform a string to lowercase in the template.

9. TitleCasePipe- used to transform a string to title case in the template.

10. AsyncPipe- used to subscribe to an Observable or Promise and return the latest value it

    has emitted.

11. KeyValuePipe- used to transform an object or a Map into an array of key-value pairs 

for display in the template.    
 
 
 import { Component } from '@angular/core';
import { CommonModule } from '@angular/common';
 
@Component({
  selector: 'app-demo-pipes',
  imports: [CommonModule],
  templateUrl: './demo-pipes.html',
  styleUrl: './demo-pipes.css',
})
export class DemoPipes {
 
  cities: string[]= ['bangalore', 'chennai', 'Delhi', 'Mumbai', 'Hyderabad', 'pune', 'Kolkata', 'Ahmedabad', 'SURAT', 'Jaipur'];
 
 
  // for JSON Pipe
  Employee = {
    id: 101,
    name: 'John Doe',
    age: 30,
    department: 'IT',
    address: {
      street: '123 Main St',
      city: 'Anytown',
      state: 'CA',
      zip: '12345'
    }
  };
 
 
  // for Date Pipe
  currentDate: Date = new Date();
 
  // for Decimal Pipe
  price: number = 1234.5678;
 
  // for Percent Pipe
  discount: number = 0.25; // 25% discount
 
  //for currency Pipe
  salary: number = 50000;
 
  //slice pipe
  message: string = 'Hello, welcome to Angular Pipes!';
}
 
 
 
<p>demo-pipes works!</p>
<p>Cities without any pipe:</p>
<ul>
    @for(city of cities; track $index)
    {
        <li>{{city}}</li>,
    }
</ul>
<p>Cities with UpperCasePipe:</p>
<ul>    
    @for(city of cities; track $index)
    {
        <li>{{city | uppercase}}</li>,
    }
</ul>
<p>Cities with LowerCasePipe:</p>
<ul>    
    @for(city of cities; track $index)
    {
        <li>{{city | lowercase}}</li>,
    }
</ul>
<p>Cities with TitleCasePipe:</p>
<ul>
    @for(city of cities; track $index)
    {
        <li>{{city | titlecase}}</li>,
    }
</ul>
<p> Employee object without JsonPipe:</p>
<p>{{Employee}}</p>
<p> Employee object with JsonPipe:</p>
<p>{{Employee | json}}</p>
 
<p>KeyValue Pipe for Employee object:</p>
<ul>
    @for(item of Employee | keyvalue ; track $index)
    {
       
        @if(typeof item.value == 'object')
        {
            <li>{{item.key}}:</li>
            <ul>
                @for(subItem of item.value | keyvalue ; track $index)
                {
                    <li>{{subItem.key}}: {{subItem.value}}</li>,
                }
            </ul>
        }
        @else
        {
            <li>{{item.key}}: {{item.value}}</li>,
        }
    }
</ul>
 
